I guess it depends on the time. If he's just a detective, there's a fine line of jurisdictional red tape you can't cross without essentially becoming a vigilante. On the other hand,if he's a specialist who's assistance is requested, then he'll have legitimate leeway to act in an official capacity within his host country's jurisdiction. Fwiw, I have a setting where a character from Victorian England travels to the US to help establish a supernatural law enforcement/corrections apparatus, where he remains after the fact. Fish-out-of-water mysteries are certainly very workable and immersive, so long as you meticulously cover any potential plot holes. Mystery is a rather notorious genre for awkwardly sleighting plot holes in a
>"BUT WHO WAS PHONE??" *fades to black*
sort of way if you end up boiling the narrative down into a state of conflict with the romance aspect and the mystery.
